Northwest Shandong Improved Cropland Management Project (hereinafter as “the proposed project”), which belongs to the type of VCS Agricultural Land Management (ALM) project activities, seeks to increase the capacity of soil organic carbon (SOC) to sequester carbon and enhance nutrients through sustainable agriculture land management (SALM) practices in northwest area of Shandong Province, P.R. China. The proposed project is expected to increase the adoption, cessation or adjustment to ALM practices through tillage management, fertilizer management and residue management. The improved ALM categories are:
	Eliminating the usage of synthetic chemical fertilizer and/or replacing the synthetic chemical fertilizers with environmentally friendly organic fertilizers; 
	Reducing tillage/ crop residue retention; 
	Rotating the commercial crop, planting a cover crop
The project area is distributed in Dezhou City, Jinan City and Binzhou City within northwest of Shandong. The terrain of the project area is flat, mostly plain depression. The project involves 36,776 ha corn field, 97,851 ha wheat field and 184,391 ha wheat maize rotation field. Northwest Shandong is a typical Warm temperate monsoon climate type with well-marked seasons. The scenario existing prior to the project’s implementation is primarily conventional tillage with synthetic fertilizer and without straw returning, which cause greater soil disturbance, increase the loss of SOC and nitrous oxide emission. Conventional practices require a significant amount of chemical and energy input and are also more likely to weaken the ecology of a landscape compared to the improved ALM practices advocated by this project. 
The estimated annual average GHG emission reductions and removals through the implementation of SALM activities in the agricultural land is 1,084,991 t CO2e year-1. Over the 20 years of the first crediting period, the project will generate an estimated removal and reduction of 21,699,822 tCO2e.

